    <h1>5</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200809/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-09"><time>2020-08-09</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline">PHO&#xAD;TOS: ABLE BAGEL, BT FILE, MELVIN CHEW, ODETTE, OUR BAT&#xAD;TER MAT&#xAD;TERS, ST FILE, SUM&#xAD;MER HILL, THE MLK CO, ZAOBAO FILE</span>
    </section>

    <p>Stay­ing liq­uid</p>
    <p>Who knew that a place like Sin­ga­pore, with scant re­sources, could pro­duce gin, whisky and vodka? Not to men­tion beer of all styles? And mead?</p>
    <p>The mak­ers are not com­pet­ing with the likes of Tan­queray, Chivas Re­gal or Grey Goose. They are putting an Asian stamp on their spir­its and brews, us­ing in­gre­di­ents from this part of the world. These would in­clude lon­gan honey (The Ori­en­tal­ist Ori­gins Vodka), am­choor or pow­dered green mango (Tan­glin Or­chid Gin), red dates and ginger (Brass Lion Pahit Pink Gin), and buah long long and sour plum (That Sin­ga­pore Beer Pro­ject Buah Long Long & Sour Plum Gose).</p>
    <p>Bars such as Na­tive in Amoy Street and Laut in Stan­ley Street are cre­at­ing cock­tails us­ing fa­mil­iar and un­fa­mil­iar lo­cal in­gre­di­ents too, in­clud­ing shi­itake and Kam­pot pep­per (Umami Five-O cock­tail from Na­tive) and gula me­laka ar­rack and tamarind (Soy cock­tail from Laut). The best ones el­e­vate the cock­tail scene here, mak­ing it very clear you are drink­ing in Sin­ga­pore, not some name­less city some­where.</p>
    <p>Other liq­uid as­sets are brew­ing or, rather, fer­ment­ing.</p>
    <p>A world is open­ing up of small-batch kom­bucha and ke­fir, some sold through home-based busi­nesses. Re­mem­ber names like Fizzi­cle, Tea Pulse and Wild Boocha if you do not want to make your own but want a healthy gut.</p>
    <p>The lac­tose-in­tol­er­ant also have a slew of op­tions when it comes to nut milks, with com­pa­nies such as The Mlk Co, Nutty Milk Fac­tory and The Gut’s Feel­ing of­fer­ing oat, al­mond, pump­kin seed and cashew milk.</p>

